Time-to-event Table as used for Forest Plot

t_forest_tte.Rd

The time-to-event forest plot table summarizes time-to-event data by groups. The function returns event counts and median survival time for each analysis arm, as well as a hazard ratio and the corresponding confidence interval from a Cox proportional hazard model.

t_forest_tte(
  tte,
  is_event,
  col_by,
  row_by_list = NULL,
  total = "ALL",
  strata_data = NULL,
  ties = "exact",
  time_unit = "month",
  conf_int = 0.95,
  dense_header = FALSE,
  table_tree = FALSE
)

Arguments

tte

(numeric vector)
Contains time to event data, currently no NA allowed
is_event

(logical value)
TRUE if event, FALSE if tte is censored
col_by

(logical, factor or data.frame)
Contains reference and comparison group information, the first level indicates the reference group. See the functions col_by_to_matrix and by_add_total.
row_by_list

(list or data.frame) of factors
Contains one factor variable to calculate the t_el_forest_tte
total

(character value)
Denotes column name of an added total column using by_add_total to col_by and col_N_add_total to col_N. If NULL no total column is added.
strata_data

(character, factor or data.frame)
Used for stratification factors If NULL, no stratified analysis is performed.
ties

(character value) the method used for tie handling in coxph.
time_unit

(character value) The unit of median survival time. Default is "months".
conf_int

(numeric value) confidence level of the interval
dense_header

(logical value) Display the table headers in multiple rows.
table_tree

(logical value)
If FALSE then a single rtable gets returned, if TRUE a node object gets returned with the elementary rtable objects.

Details

Cox proportional hazard model is used for hazard ratio calculation

The returned table contains one row per analysis within a subgroup of data (indicated by the row name). The analysis is summarized with the following 9 columns:

1

Total n the total number of subjects included in analysis population

2-4

Survival statistics for reference arm, n and Events are the total number of patients and the number of events in reference arm, respectively. Median (month) is the survival time estimated by Kaplan-Meier method. Time unit can be modified per study needs.

5-7

same analysis as for reference arm now for comparison arm

8

Hazard Ratio ranges from 0 to infinity. The hazard ratio is an estimate of the ratio of the hazard rate in the comparison group versus that in the reference group. Univariate Cox proportional hazard model is applied to obtain the estimated hazard ratio. Hazard ratio > 1 implies better treatment effect in reference arm, and hazard ratio < 1 when comparison arm is better.

9

Wald CI The confidence interval indicates the level of uncertainty around the measure of effect (Hazard Ratio). Because only a small sample of the overall population is included in the analysis, by having an upper and lower confidence limit we can infer that the true treatment effect lies in between. By default, the 95 interval is calculated. If it includes 1, then we say that the difference between two arms is not significant at a significance level of 0.05.

See also

t_el_forest_tte, t_tte

Examples

library(random.cdisc.data)
library(dplyr)

ADSL <- radsl(cached = TRUE)

ADTTE <- radtte(cached = TRUE)
ADTTE_f <- ADTTE %>%
  dplyr::filter(PARAMCD == "OS", ARMCD %in% c("ARM B", "ARM A")) %>%
  mutate(ARMCD = droplevels(ARMCD))

tbl <- t_forest_tte(
  tte = ADTTE_f$AVAL,
  is_event = ADTTE_f$CNSR == 0,
  col_by = ADTTE_f$ARMCD,
  row_by_list = droplevels(ADTTE_f[, c("SEX", "RACE")]),
  ties = "exact",
  conf_int = 0.9,
  dense_header = TRUE
)
#> Warning: Ran out of iterations and did not converge

tbl2 <- t_forest_tte(
  tte = ADTTE_f$AVAL,
  is_event = ADTTE_f$CNSR == 0,
  col_by = ADTTE_f$ARMCD,
  row_by_list = droplevels(ADTTE_f[,  "BMRKR2" ]),
  strata_data = ADTTE_f[ , c("STRATA1", "STRATA2")],
  ties = "exact",
  dense_header = TRUE
)

tbl2
